ce:section.ce:para:
Tetracycline is a broad-spectrum antibiotic, which have been widely used in medicine because of their inhibition of bacterial growth [27–30]. However, the abuse of tetracycline also increases the threat to human health. In this work, we developed a facile RT synthesis strategy for preparing highly-fluorescent fluorine-doped CQDs (F-CQDs) with good crystallinity by using tetrafluorobenzoquinone (TFBQ) and ethylenediamine (EDA) as the precursors. Only Schiff base condensation can occur between TFBQ and EDA, avoiding the production of other side reactions, which can be used to prepare the F-CQDs with high quality (Scheme 1
                     ). The as-prepared F-CQDs show strong blue FL emission with an absolute QY of about 39%, which is the highest value recorded for CDs prepared by RT synthesis. Importantly, the as-obtained F-CQDs have an excitation peak at 360 nm, which has a great spectral overlap with absorption of tetracycline at 358 nm. Thus tetracycline has a strong ability to shield the excitation light of F-CQDs, resulting in a strong inner filter effect (IFE) between F-CQDs and tetracycline. The FL intensity ratio (F
                     0/F) of the F-CQDs is proportional to the concentration of tetracycline in the range of 0.1 – 25 μM with the limit of detection (LOD) of 85 nM (3σ/k). This sensing strategy is facile, rapid, and highly-selective, which shows a great application prospect in the detection of tetracycline.
